<subSubSection id="C31C65453034021EF5CBABFD9F41FDE6" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB936CE3034021EF5CBABFD9F41FDE6" blockId="0.[151,1436,1968,2034]" lastBlockId="1.[151,1437,152,538]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D4D3034021FF441ABFD9AE5F835" box="[285,506,1968,1993]" class="Insecta" family="Sphingidae" genus="Sphingonaepiopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B972EADC3034021FF441ABFD9AE5F835" box="[285,506,1968,1993]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Sphingonaepiopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises some of the smallest of all hawkmoths, with wingspans of 
<quantity id="4CFE9B2B3034021FF00EABFD9BD6F80E" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" unit="mm" value="30.0" valueMax="35.0" valueMin="25.0">25â€“35 mm</quantity>
. There are currently seven recognized species (
<bibRefCitation id="EF974B3F3034021FF7AAAB959F3EF80E" author="Kitching" box="[758,1057,2008,2034]" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" refString="Kitching, I. J. &amp; Cadiou, J. - M. (2000) Hawkmoths of the world: an annotated and illustrated revisionary checklist. Cornell University Press, Ithaca, 226 pp." type="book" year="2000">
Kitching &amp; Cadiou 
<number id="3DCE24E93034021FF6BEAB959F3EF80E" box="[994,1057,2008,2034]" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), distributed throughout the Old World. 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D4D3035021EF5B3ACD59A80FF4D" box="[239,415,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Sphingidae" genus="Sphingonaepiopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gorgoniades">
<emphasis id="B972EADC3035021EF5B3ACD59A80FF4D" box="[239,415,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">S. gorgoniades</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D4D3035021EF480ACD59826FF4E" authority="Graeser 1892" authorityName="Graeser" authorityYear="1892" box="[476,825,152,178]" class="Insecta" family="Sphingidae" genus="Sphingonaepiopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kuldjaensis">
<emphasis id="B972EADC3035021EF480ACD59960FF4D" box="[476,639,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">S. kuldjaensis</emphasis>
(Graeser 
<number id="3DCE24E93035021EF7A9ACD5982EFF4E" box="[757,817,152,178]" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" value="1892.0">1892</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
have Palaearctic distributions; the former has been recorded from SE Europe, east to the southern Urals, 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF657AC8D9885FF26" box="[779,922,192,218]" name="Afghanistan" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Afghanistan</collectingCountry>
and NE 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF15EAC8D9F6AFF26" box="[1026,1141,192,218]" name="Tajikistan" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Tajikistan</collectingCountry>
(possibly reaching as far as Eastern Siberia, see below), and the latter is restricted to the mountains of Central Asia, from NE 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF06EACA59BD6FED6" name="Afghanistan" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Afghanistan</collectingCountry>
, through the Tian Shan, to eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF73BAD5D99EFFED6" box="[615,752,272,298]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
and NW 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF638AD5D98B1FED6" box="[868,942,272,298]" name="China" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">China</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D4D3035021EF6E6AD5D9E17FED6" authority="Rothschild 1904" authorityName="Rothschild" authorityYear="1904" box="[954,1288,272,298]" class="Insecta" family="Sphingidae" genus="Sphingonaepiopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ansorgei">
<emphasis id="B972EADC3035021EF6E6AD5D9F22FED5" box="[954,1085,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">S. ansorgei</emphasis>
Rothschild 
<number id="3DCE24E93035021EF191AD5D9E17FED6" box="[1229,1288,272,298]" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" value="1904.0">1904</number>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D4D3035021EF01FAD5D9E83FED5" box="[1347,1436,272,297]" class="Insecta" family="Sphingidae" genus="Sphingonaepiopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nana">
<emphasis id="B972EADC3035021EF01FAD5D9E83FED5" box="[1347,1436,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">S. nana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are Afrotropical; the former is restricted to East Africa (from 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF639AD7598ADFEAE" box="[869,946,312,338]" name="Kenya" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Kenya</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF6B6AD759F5AFEAE" box="[1002,1093,312,338]" name="Uganda" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Uganda</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF136AD759E1AFEAE" box="[1130,1285,312,338]" name="South Africa" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">South Africa</collectingCountry>
), and the latter occurs throughout sub-Saharan Africa, also in the Arabian Peninsula, and is here confirmed for the first time from 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF448ADC59A5CFE5E" box="[276,323,392,418]" name="Iran" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Iran</collectingCountry>
(see below). 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D4D3035021EF4B8ADC5980BFE5E" authority="Clark 1929" authorityName="Clark" authorityYear="1929" box="[484,788,392,418]" class="Insecta" family="Sphingidae" genus="Sphingonaepiopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="malgassica">
<emphasis id="B972EADC3035021EF4B8ADC59998FE5D" box="[484,647,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">S. malgassica</emphasis>
Clark 
<number id="3DCE24E93035021EF785ADC5980BFE5E" box="[729,788,392,418]" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" value="1929.0">1929</number>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D4D3035021EF612ADC59F8FFE5E" authority="Mabille 1880" authorityName="Mabille" authorityYear="1880" box="[846,1168,392,418]" class="Insecta" family="Sphingidae" genus="Sphingonaepiopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurus">
<emphasis id="B972EADC3035021EF612ADC598C8FE5D" box="[846,983,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">S. obscurus</emphasis>
(Mabille 
<number id="3DCE24E93035021EF110ADC59F97FE5E" box="[1100,1160,392,418]" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" value="1880.0">1880</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
are endemic to 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF013ADC59BFBFE36" name="Madagascar" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
, the former restricted to the south of the island, the latter found throughout (
<bibRefCitation id="EF974B3F3035021EF101ADFD9E0DFE36" author="Griveaud" box="[1117,1298,432,458]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" refString="Griveaud, P. (1959) Insectes Lepidopteres Sphingidae. Faune de Madagascar, 8, 1 - 161." type="journal article" year="1959">
Griveaud 
<number id="3DCE24E93035021EF18FADFD9E0DFE36" box="[1235,1298,432,458]" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" value="1959.0">1959</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Finally, 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D4D3035021EF0DAADFD9BEFFE0D" class="Insecta" family="Sphingidae" genus="Sphingonaepiopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pumilio">
<emphasis id="B972EADC3035021EF0DAADFD9BEFFE0D" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">S. pumilio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF974B3F3035021EF5A3AD959AD2FE0E" author="Boisduval" box="[255,461,472,498]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" refString="Boisduval, J. B. A. E. de. [1875] (1874) Sphingides, Sesiides, Castnides. In: Boisduval, J. B. A. E. de &amp; Guenee, A. (Eds.), Histoire naturelle des insectes. Species general des Lepidopteres Heteroceres, Vol. 1. Librairie Encyclopedique de Roret, Paris, pp. 1 - 568 + 1 - 4." type="book chapter" year="1875">
Boisduval [
<number id="3DCE24E93035021EF4DAAD959AD9FE0E" box="[390,454,472,498]" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" value="1875.0">1875</number>
]
</bibRefCitation>
) is SE Asian, occurring from NE 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF604AD959888FE0E" box="[856,919,472,498]" name="India" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">India</collectingCountry>
, through 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF159AD959F4AFE0E" box="[1029,1109,472,498]" name="Myanmar" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Burma</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF1D0AD959FE8FE0E" box="[1164,1271,472,498]" name="Thailand" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Thailand</collectingCountry>
, to Peninsular 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF5CBAE4D9A1DFDE6" box="[151,258,512,538]" name="Malaysia" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF467AE4D9AAAFDE6" box="[315,437,512,538]" name="Singapore" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Singapore</collectingCountry>
, with populations also in eastern and south-eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F311765E3035021EF14CAE4D9F45FDE6" box="[1040,1114,512,538]" name="China" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">China</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
